<td valign="top"><div>
      
<font size="+4" color=#990000>In English</font> the verb "to be" plays many roles.  It can:<br><br>


<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>Indicate existence:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>Describe something:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>Show location:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>Convey emotions:</strong></font></div></td>


<td><div><u>There is</u> a fly in my soup!<br>
 The fly <u>is pretty</u>!<br>
The fly <u>is in my soup</u>!<br>
The fly <u>is happy</u>!</div></td>

<td><img src="images/insect_clipart_fly.gif" border="0" alt="fly"></td>
</tr>
</table>



<br>
<font size="+4" color=#990000>In Spanish</font>, one verb cannot play all these roles.  The roles are 
divided among three verbs: <font color="#EE871B"><b>"ser", "estar",</b></font> and <font color="#EE871B"><b>"haber"</b></font>.<br><br>

<table align="center" cellpadding=5 bgcolor="#E0F0F5" width="850">
<tr>
<td><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>To indicate existence:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>To describe:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>To show location:</strong></font><br>
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>To convey emotions:</strong></font></div></td>


<td><div> Spanish uses the verb <font color="#EE871B"><b>"haber"</b></font><br>
Spanish uses the verb <font color="#EE871B"><b>"ser"</b></font><br>
Spanish uses the verb <font color="#EE871B"><b>"estar"</b></font><br>
Spanish uses the verb <font color="#EE871B"><b>"estar"</b></font></div></td>


</tr>
</table>


<br>

</font></div>
